.TH "TEMPORAL.ZONEDDATETIME.ROUND" "3JS" "December 8, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Temporal.ZonedDateTime.round \- Temporal.ZonedDateTime.prototype.round()
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]round()\f[B]\f[R] method of
\f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] instances returns a new
\f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] object representing this date\-time
rounded to the given unit.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
round(smallestUnit)
round(options)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]smallestUnit\f[R]
A string representing the \f[CR]smallestUnit\f[R] option.
This is a convenience overload, so \f[CR]round(smallestUnit)\f[R] is
equivalent to \f[CR]round({ smallestUnit })\f[R], where
\f[CR]smallestUnit\f[R] is a string.
.TP
\f[B]options\f[R]
An object containing some or all of the following properties (in the
order they are retrieved and validated):
.RS
.TP
\f[B]roundingIncrement\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
A number (truncated to an integer) representing the rounding increment
in the given \f[CR]smallestUnit\f[R].
Defaults to \f[CR]1\f[R].
For all values of \f[CR]smallestUnit\f[R] except \f[CR]\(dqday\(dq\f[R],
the increment must be a divisor of the maximum value of the unit; for
example, if the unit is hours, the increment must be a divisor of 24 and
must not be 24 itself, which means it can be 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 8, or 12.
For \f[CR]\(dqday\(dq\f[R], the increment must be 1.
.TP
\f[B]roundingMode\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
A string specifying how to round off the fractional part of
\f[CR]smallestUnit\f[R].
See \f[CR]Intl.NumberFormat()\f[R].
Defaults to \f[CR]\(dqhalfExpand\(dq\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]smallestUnit\f[R]
A string representing the smallest unit to include in the output.
The value must be one of the following: \f[CR]\(dqday\(dq\f[R],
\f[CR]\(dqhour\(dq\f[R], \f[CR]\(dqminute\(dq\f[R],
\f[CR]\(dqsecond\(dq\f[R], \f[CR]\(dqmillisecond\(dq\f[R],
\f[CR]\(dqmicrosecond\(dq\f[R], \f[CR]\(dqnanosecond\(dq\f[R], or their
plural forms.
For units larger than \f[CR]\(dqnanosecond\(dq\f[R], fractional parts of
the \f[CR]smallestUnit\f[R] will be rounded according to the
\f[CR]roundingIncrement\f[R] and \f[CR]roundingMode\f[R] settings.
.RE
.SS Return value
A new \f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] object representing this
date\-time rounded to the given unit, where all units smaller than
\f[CR]smallestUnit\f[R] are zeroed out.
.PP
If \f[CR]smallestUnit\f[R] is \f[CR]\(dqday\(dq\f[R], the returned
date\-time will be the start of day of this date or the next day,
depending on the \f[CR]roundingMode\f[R] and the distance to these two
instants.
Otherwise, the rounding is first performed on its
\f[CR]PlainDateTime\f[R] (same as
\f[CR]Temporal.PlainDateTime.prototype.round()\f[R]), and then
re\-interpreted in the same time zone, with
\f[CR]disambiguation: \(dqcompatible\(dq, offset: \(dqprefer\(dq\f[R].
See ambiguity and gaps from local time to UTC time and offset ambiguity.
.SS Exceptions
.TP
\f[B]RangeError\f[R]
Thrown if any of the options is invalid.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Rounding off small units
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] zdt = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(
  \(dq2021\-07\-01T12:34:56.123456789[America/New_York]\(dq,
);
\f[B]const\f[R] nearestMillisecond = zdt.round(\(dqmillisecond\(dq);
console.log(nearestMillisecond.toString()); \f[I]// 2021\-07\-01T12:34:56.123\-04:00[America/New_York]\f[R]

\f[B]const\f[R] nearestHalfHour = zdt.round({
  smallestUnit: \(dqminute\(dq,
  roundingIncrement: 30,
});
console.log(nearestHalfHour.toString()); \f[I]// 2021\-07\-01T12:30:00\-04:00[America/New_York]\f[R]

\f[B]const\f[R] nextDay = zdt.round({ smallestUnit: \(dqday\(dq, roundingMode: \(dqceil\(dq });
console.log(nextDay.toString()); \f[I]// 2021\-07\-02T00:00:00\-04:00[America/New_York]\f[R]
.EE
.SS Ambiguity after rounding
It\(cqs possible that the rounded date\-time is ambiguous in the given
time zone.
The ambiguity is always resolved using
\f[CR]disambiguation: \(dqcompatible\(dq, offset: \(dqprefer\(dq\f[R].
Here\(cqs a quick example:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] zdt = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(
  \(dq2024\-03\-10T01:00:00\-05:00[America/New_York]\(dq,
);
\f[B]const\f[R] rounded = zdt.round({ smallestUnit: \(dqhour\(dq, roundingIncrement: 2 });
\f[I]// The result is supposed to be 2024\-03\-10T02:00:00\-05:00[America/New_York],\f[R]
\f[I]// but this time does not exist. \(gadisambiguation: \(dqcompatible\(dq\(ga tells us to move\f[R]
\f[I]// forward by 1 hour.\f[R]
console.log(rounded.toString()); \f[I]// 2024\-03\-10T03:00:00\-04:00[America/New_York]\f[R]
.EE
.SH SEE ALSO
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R]
